Date: June 1, 1995  
Abstract: We describe Facet-Based Learning (FBL) for undergraduate statistic education. This instructional methodology attempts to bridge the gap between students knowledge and experts knowledge by making students prior knowledge and understandings explicit and then facilitating student progress towards expert-like behavior. Researchers and teachers developed FBL in the context of high school physics, and their results demonstrate the effectiveness of FBL in that setting. Application of FBL to large undergraduate classes requires extensive computing support. We have developed WorldWide Web-based computing tools and evaluated both the tools and FBL as a whole. Our results suggest that both FBL and the computing tools are effective at the college level. 
